<br>
Its called splitting the pairs as normal house wiring has 2 pair voice wiring and you only use 1 pair per voice line. The problem is you are using shitty voice grade lines to try and pass data, which is often the reason for slow transfer rates. <br>
<br>
If you are going to get ISDN I would make sure you have tried every single other available connection type on the planet. ISDN is outdated technology and extremely expensive. Basically you can get 2 64k Bearer channels for a grand total of 128k dedicated connectivity, but unless you have a trust fund and unlimited cash flow you wont be able to afford to stay connected for more than a couple hours a month. <br>
<br>
Getting two dial up lines is certainly and option and you dont need to get a special modem for it or a 300 dollar office connect box. Get two modems and two voice lines into your house(after you have verified that your ISP will support MPP...multi-point protocol connections). If they ask you what is MPP, ask to speak to another tech or escalate the call until you get someone with a clue.  Just for an example here is one website or at least the first one I found on a search:<br>
<br>
